title: For Sale:  Mint Condition Sig Sauer Mosquito .22LR +holster +2nd magazine
postcontent:
I'm selling my mint-condition, hardly-used, Sig Sauer Mosquito 22LR. I'd be surprised if this has more than 250 rounds through it. To give you an idea of how this firearm has been cared for: anytime it has been used it has been carefully cleaned afterwards (and I doubt it's been to the range more than 5 times).

The Mosquito is 90% of the size of the P226 and is a great gun. Easy (and inexpensive) to shoot. 

I have a friend who had never really fired a handgun before who was going through her CCW training course. With barely any practice (less than 10 rounds) she qualified with this firearm.

Why did I buy it? It's a Sig Sauer. Plus, a 22LR. And, it has a thumb safety (important feature for me: I know, lots of people don't use them and I understand). However, I haven't purchased any other Sig Sauer's and am now standardizing on Ruger's (and the Ruger thumb safeties flip the opposite direction).

You can see in the photos that the gun is in mint condition. Included with the gun:
- 2x 10-round Sig factory magazines
- A Fobus paddle holster
- The original case
- Registration card, user manual
- Ruger gun lock
- Spare recoil spring (the reason many semi-automatic 22's have a reputation for not reliably feeding ammunition is the varying quality of 22LR ammunition - to give you an idea of Sig Sauer quality: they knew that is what causes issues with semi-automatic 22's and included two springs with the Mosquito --- a stiffer one that works best with higher-powered/premium 22 ammo, and a looser spring that works better with bulk/regular 22 ammo). Speaking of how the firearm handles 22 ammo: it's done quite well, and I just use bulk 22 (not the higher-powered 22). I don't know if I have the stiffer or looser recoil spring in the firearm.

I'm listing it at $380 but would consider a $360 offer.

title: For Sale:  Winchester M-1 Garand Rifle
postcontent:
For Sale:

Winchester M-1

This is a very nice rifle with good finish that I would rate at 80-90% overall. I believe the finish to be original across the rifle. The barrel is WRA and gauges a 1.5 or so at the throat. I don’t have a muzzle gauge. The rifling is very strong in the barrel. The chamber face is not parkerized. 

I bought this rifle as-is except for the stock that is on it. The stock that it came with was a beater DAS stock and I don’t have any clue why what looks to be a nearly complete WRA rifle wound up with the wrong wood on it but this stock is nicer and has good grain. It is not a WRA stock. 

I can’t remember all the ins and outs of Garands anymore so please email me if I get something wrong or if you have a question.

I believe all the parts are WRA except for the stock, its hardware and the hammer is an SA -2.

The op rod is WRA and is uncut with the angled bolt housing outer face. The follower rod is a short fork. The gas system is all WRA I believe and it has the early plug. The front sight is wider than an SA and so I think it is WRA. The safety is a WRA -4 flat-top. The bolt is WRA -1. If I remember right the rear hand guard of a WRA has a small indent where the op rod angles under and this has that. The bands appear to be WRA. The hammer spring plunger does not have ears so I am not certain that that is original or not. 

Like I said, please ask any questions you might have and let me know if I made a mistake on any of the identifications.

You can see an album of photos of the Winchester at this link:
http://s200.photobucket.com/user/hzamar/library/WRA%20M1?sort=3&page=1

I am asking $2200 for the rifle. I am located in Glendale, AZ if anyone is local and would like to see it in person.

Thanks,
Herb
